              <resources id="29"/>
              <answerOptions id="30">
                <MCAnswer id="31">
                  <order>0</order>
                  <rule>CORRECT</rule>
                  <text>&lt;div&gt;The graph must be 2-connected (vertex connectivity $\geq 2$&lt;/div&gt;</text>
                  <variableName></variableName>
                  <mcstage reference="15"/>
                </MCAnswer>
                <MCAnswer id="32">
                  <order>1</order>
                  <rule>WRONG</rule>
                  <text>&lt;div&gt;The graph must be connected but can be 1-connected&lt;/div&gt;</text>
                  <variableName></variableName>
                  <mcstage reference="15"/>
                </MCAnswer>
                <MCAnswer id="33">
                  <order>2</order>
                  <rule>WRONG</rule>
                  <text>&lt;div&gt;The graph must be 3-connected (vertex connectivity $\geq 3$)&lt;/div&gt;</text>
                  <variableName></variableName>
                  <mcstage reference="15"/>
                </MCAnswer>
                <MCAnswer id="34">
                  <order>3</order>
                  <rule>WRONG</rule>
                  <text>&lt;div&gt;The graph can be disconnected if the cycle is in one component&lt;/div&gt;</text>
                  <variableName></variableName>
                  <mcstage reference="15"/>
                </MCAnswer>
              </answerOptions>
              <randomize>false</randomize>
              <maxSelections>1</maxSelections>
              <correctAnswerFeedback>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Correct. A Hamiltonian cycle visits every vertex exactly once and&lt;br&gt;returns to the start. This creates a cycle subgraph that spans&lt;br&gt;all vertices. Since a cycle is 2-connected (you can remove any&lt;br&gt;single vertex and still have a path between remaining vertices),&lt;br&gt;the entire graph must be at least 2-connected. This means there&lt;br&gt;are at least two vertex-disjoint paths between any pair of&lt;br&gt;vertices. Note that the graph could have higher connectivity, but&lt;br&gt;2-connectivity is guaranteed by the existence of a Hamiltonian&lt;br&gt;cycle.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: The graph must be 2-connected (vertex connectivity&lt;br&gt;$\geq 2$)&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</correctAnswerFeedback>
              <pointMode>MANUAL</pointMode>
              <feedbackDisplayMode>NEVER</feedbackDisplayMode>
              <defaultResult>0</defaultResult>
              <extraFeedbacks id="35">
                <de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback id="36">
                  <feedback__order>0</feedback__order>
                  <stage reference="15"/>
                  <expression id="37">
                    <code>![input=mcindex_0]&amp;&amp;[input=mcindex_1]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_2]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_3]</code>
                    <domain>MATH</domain>
