                  <condition id="38">
                    <code></code>
                    <domain>MATH</domain>
                  </condition>
                  <result>0</result>
                  <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. A graph with a Hamiltonian cycle must be more than just connected. It must be 2-connected. A 1-connected graph has a cut vertex (a vertex whose removal disconnects the graph). But if a graph has a Hamiltonian cycle, you can remove any single vertex and still traverse all remaining vertices along the cycle. For example, a tree is 1-connected but can never have a Hamiltonian&lt;br&gt;cycle (except for $K_2$, which is just an edge).&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: The graph must be 2-connected (vertex connectivity $\geq 2$)&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
                </de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback>
                <de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback id="39">
                  <feedback__order>1</feedback__order>
                  <stage reference="15"/>
                  <expression id="40">
                    <code>![input=mcindex_0]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_1]&amp;&amp;[input=mcindex_2]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_3]</code>
                    <domain>MATH</domain>
                  </expression>
                  <condition id="41">
                    <code></code>
                    <domain>MATH</domain>
                  </condition>
                  <result>0</result>
                  <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. While a Hamiltonian cycle guarantees 2-connectivity, it doesn&apos;t guarantee 3-connectivity. Consider a cycle graph $C_n$ itself - it has a Hamiltonian cycle (the cycle visits all vertices) but is only 2-connected, not 3-connected. Removing any two vertices from a cycle disconnects it. Many graphs with Hamiltonian cycles have vertex connectivity exactly 2.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: The graph must be 2-connected (vertex connectivity&lt;br&gt;$\geq 2$)&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
                </de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback>
                <de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback id="42">
                  <feedback__order>2</feedback__order>
                  <stage reference="15"/>
                  <expression id="43">
                    <code>![input=mcindex_0]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_1]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_2]&amp;&amp;[input=mcindex_3]</code>
                    <domain>MATH</domain>
                  </expression>
                  <condition id="44">
                    <code></code>
                    <domain>MATH</domain>
                  </condition>
                  <result>0</result>
                  <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. A Hamiltonian cycle must visit every vertex in the graph exactly once. If the graph is disconnected, there&apos;s no way to create a single cycle that reaches vertices in different components. By definition, a Hamiltonian cycle requires the graph to be connected. In fact, it requires even stronger connectivity: The graph must be 2-connected.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: The graph must be 2-connected (vertex connectivity&lt;br&gt;$\geq 2$)&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
                </de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback>
