            <MCAnswer id="56">
              <order>0</order>
              <rule>CORRECT</rule>
              <text>&lt;div&gt;At least 5 (i.e., $\delta \geq n/2$ where $n = 10$)&lt;/div&gt;</text>
              <variableName></variableName>
              <mcstage reference="10"/>
            </MCAnswer>
            <MCAnswer id="57">
              <order>1</order>
              <rule>WRONG</rule>
              <text>&lt;div&gt;At least 6 (i.e., $\delta &amp;gt; n/2$ where $n = 10$)&lt;/div&gt;</text>
              <variableName></variableName>
              <mcstage reference="10"/>
            </MCAnswer>
            <MCAnswer id="58">
              <order>2</order>
              <rule>WRONG</rule>
              <text>&lt;div&gt;At least 9 (i.e., $\delta \geq n-1$ where $n = 10$)&lt;/div&gt;</text>
              <variableName></variableName>
              <mcstage reference="10"/>
            </MCAnswer>
            <MCAnswer id="59">
              <order>3</order>
              <rule>WRONG</rule>
              <text>&lt;div&gt;At least 4 (i.e., $\delta \geq n/2 - 1$ where $n = 10$)&lt;/div&gt;</text>
              <variableName></variableName>
              <mcstage reference="10"/>
            </MCAnswer>
          </answerOptions>
          <randomize>false</randomize>
          <maxSelections>1</maxSelections>
          <correctAnswerFeedback>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Correct. Dirac&apos;s theorem states that a simple graph with $n \geq 3$ vertices has a Hamiltonian cycle if every vertex has degree at least $n/2$. For a 10-vertex graph, $n/2 = 5$, so every vertex must have degree at least 5. This is a sufficient (but not necessary) condition - graphs with lower minimum degree might still have Hamiltonian cycles, but Dirac&apos;s theorem doesn&apos;t guarantee it. Note that the condition is $\delta \geq n/2$, which for even $n$ means at least half the vertices.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: At least 5 (i.e., $\delta \geq n/2$ where $n = 10$)&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</correctAnswerFeedback>
          <pointMode>MANUAL</pointMode>
          <feedbackDisplayMode>NEVER</feedbackDisplayMode>
          <defaultResult>0</defaultResult>
          <extraFeedbacks id="60">
            <de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback id="61">
              <feedback__order>0</feedback__order>
              <stage reference="10"/>
              <expression id="62">
                <code>![input=mcindex_0]&amp;&amp;[input=mcindex_1]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_2]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_3]</code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </expression>
              <condition id="63">
                <code></code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </condition>
              <result>0</result>
              <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. You&apos;re using a strict inequality ($\delta &amp;gt; n/2$), but Dirac&apos;s theorem uses a non-strict inequality. The correct statement is $\delta \geq n/2$, not $\delta &amp;gt; n/2$. For $n = 10$, this means&lt;br&gt;degree at least 5, not strictly greater than 5. The theorem guarantees a Hamiltonian cycle when every vertex has degree at least $n/2$ (including exactly $n/2$).&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: At least 5 (i.e., $\delta \geq n/2$ where $n = 10$)&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
            </de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback>
            <de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback id="64">
              <feedback__order>1</feedback__order>
              <stage reference="10"/>
              <expression id="65">
                <code>![input=mcindex_0]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_1]&amp;&amp;[input=mcindex_2]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_3]</code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </expression>
              <condition id="66">
                <code></code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </condition>
              <result>0</result>
              <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. While a graph where every vertex has degree at least&lt;br&gt;$n-1$ would certainly have a Hamiltonian cycle (in fact, $K_n$&lt;br&gt;has all degrees equal to $n-1$), this is far too strong a&lt;br&gt;requirement. Dirac&apos;s theorem gives a much weaker sufficient&lt;br&gt;condition: degree at least $n/2 = 5$ for a 10-vertex graph. Your&lt;br&gt;answer would require degree at least 9, which is nearly a complete&lt;br&gt;graph.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: At least 5 (i.e., $\delta \geq n/2$ where $n = 10$)&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
            </de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback>
            <de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback id="67">
              <feedback__order>2</feedback__order>
              <stage reference="10"/>
              <expression id="68">
                <code>![input=mcindex_0]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_1]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_2]&amp;&amp;[input=mcindex_3]</code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </expression>
              <condition id="69">
                <code></code>
                <domain>MATH</domain>
              </condition>
              <result>0</result>
              <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. This underestimates the degree requirement. Dirac&apos;s&lt;br&gt;theorem requires degree at least $n/2$, not $n/2 - 1$. For&lt;br&gt;$n = 10$, this means at least 5, not at least 4. A graph with&lt;br&gt;minimum degree 4 is not guaranteed to have a Hamiltonian cycle&lt;br&gt;by Dirac&apos;s theorem. The difference of 1 matters - there are&lt;br&gt;counterexamples with minimum degree 4 that lack Hamiltonian&lt;br&gt;cycles.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: At least 5 (i.e., $\delta \geq n/2$ where $n = 10$)&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
            </de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback>
