        <MCAnswer id="82">
          <order>1</order>
          <rule>WRONG</rule>
          <text>&lt;div&gt;The number of odd-degree vertices must be odd&lt;/div&gt;</text>
          <variableName></variableName>
          <mcstage reference="5"/>
        </MCAnswer>
        <MCAnswer id="83">
          <order>2</order>
          <rule>WRONG</rule>
          <text>&lt;div&gt;Every graph must have at least one odd-degree vertex&lt;/div&gt;</text>
          <variableName></variableName>
          <mcstage reference="5"/>
        </MCAnswer>
        <MCAnswer id="84">
          <order>3</order>
          <rule>WRONG</rule>
          <text>&lt;div&gt;The number of odd-degree vertices equals the number of edges&lt;/div&gt;</text>
          <variableName></variableName>
          <mcstage reference="5"/>
        </MCAnswer>
      </answerOptions>
      <randomize>false</randomize>
      <maxSelections>1</maxSelections>
      <correctAnswerFeedback>&lt;div&gt;Correct. The Handshaking Lemma states that the sum of all vertex degrees equals twice the number of edges (since each edge contributes to exactly two vertices). This sum must be even.&lt;/div&gt;&#xd;
&lt;div&gt;Solution: The number of odd-degree vertices must be even&lt;/div&gt;</correctAnswerFeedback>
