        <de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback id="86">
          <feedback__order>0</feedback__order>
          <stage reference="5"/>
          <expression id="87">
            <code>![input=mcindex_0]&amp;&amp;[input=mcindex_1]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_2]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_3]</code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </expression>
          <condition id="88">
            <code></code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </condition>
          <result>0</result>
          <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. This contradicts the Handshaking Lemma. The sum of all&lt;br&gt;degrees equals twice the number of edges, which is always even. Since even-degree vertices contribute an even sum, the odd-degree vertices must also sum to an even number. You can only get an even sum from odd numbers if you have an even count of them, not an odd count.&lt;br&gt;Solution: The number of odd-degree vertices must be even&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
        </de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback>
        <de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback id="89">
          <feedback__order>1</feedback__order>
          <stage reference="5"/>
          <expression id="90">
            <code>![input=mcindex_0]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_1]&amp;&amp;[input=mcindex_2]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_3]</code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </expression>
          <condition id="91">
            <code></code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </condition>
          <result>0</result>
          <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. Many graphs have no odd-degree vertices at all. For example, any cycle graph has all vertices with degree 2 (even). Complete graphs $K_n$ where $n$ is odd have all vertices with&lt;br&gt;even degree $n-1$. The Handshaking Lemma doesn&apos;t require odd-degree vertices to exist - it only states that if they do exist, there must be an even number of them.&lt;br&gt;Solution: The number of odd-degree vertices must be even&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
        </de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback>
        <de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback id="92">
          <feedback__order>2</feedback__order>
          <stage reference="5"/>
          <expression id="93">
            <code>![input=mcindex_0]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_1]&amp;&amp;![input=mcindex_2]&amp;&amp;[input=mcindex_3]</code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </expression>
          <condition id="94">
            <code></code>
            <domain>MATH</domain>
          </condition>
          <result>0</result>
          <feedbackText>&lt;div&gt;Incorrect. The number of odd-degree vertices and the number of edges are generally unrelated. For example, a triangle ($K_3$) has 3 edges but 0 odd-degree vertices. A path of 3 vertices has 2 edges and 2 odd-degree vertices. The Handshaking Lemma tells us that the sum of all degrees equals twice the number of edges, and as a consequence, the number of odd-degree vertices must be even. Solution: The number of odd-degree vertices must be even&lt;/div&gt;</feedbackText>
        </de.uni__due.s3.jack3.entities.stagetypes.mc.MCFeedback>
